Consonants.

The consonants have in general the same sounds as in English.

1. C and g are soft before e, i, y, ae and oe; eg, A-ge'silf-ns, Conci-ra.

2. ch always has the sonnd of k; eg, Chi-os.

3. C, s, and tbefore i preceded by an accented syllable and followed by a vowel have the sonnd of sh; eg, Sic-yon (slah-eon), Boe-o-ti-a.

4. After s, t, or x, t keeps its hard sound; eg, Clas-fidium. So also in the termination, dion.
